                        Pompeius. Ca[e]sar. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Pompey"/>
                <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Pompey; Caesar. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        De Pompeij rebus gestis tam magnific&egrave; Liuius, ut ab ipso Augusto audiret, Pompeianus. At Lucanus Pompeio quant&ograve; 
                        liberalior: Ca[e]sari iniquior? Plinius, utriq[ue] aequus; et Plutarchus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                <person name="Pompey"/>
                <person name="Augustus"/>
                <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                <person name="Lucan"/>
                <person name="Pliny the Elder"/>
                <person name="Plutarch"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Livy wrote so proudly of Pompey's achievements, that he was called ‘Pompeianus’ by Augustus himself. But how much more generous to Pompey and 
                harsh on Caesar was Lucan! Pliny was fair to both, as was Plutarch.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Huc Pompeij grauis prouincia de tot Romanorum corruptis legibus, moribusq[ue] corrigendis: apud C[ornelium] Tacitum, Annalium l. 3. 
                        Locus est subtili disquisitione dignus.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Pompey"/>
                    <book title="The Annals"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                On this point Pompey’s serious task of reforming a great many corrupt laws and customs of the Romans, see Tacitus, bk. 3 of the Annals. 
                This is a place that is worth meticulous scrutiny. 
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Catilina.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Lucius Sergius Catilina"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Catiline.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Caesar.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Caesar.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Qua[e] iam gerebantur, summo sunt gesta ingenio, et industria. Et hoc aureum est speculum Romana[e] prudentia[e], et fortitudinis: 
                        utinam etiam iustitia[e], et temperantia[e]. Nemo plura paucioribus de Pompeio, et Ca[e]sare, qu&agrave;m Velleius, et Plinius. Da 
                        mihi scriptores, qui quasi oculari demonstratione repraesentant personas. In quo etiam uiuido descriptionis genere excellit Liuius: 
                        prop&egrave; unicus Iconismi artifex.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Pompey"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
                    <person name="Pliny the Elder"/>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                What is accomplished at this point, are deeds of the highest ingenuity and industry. And this a the golden mirror of Roman sagacity and 
                courage, if only also of justice and restraint. Nobody wrote more in fewer words about Pompey and Caesar than Velleius Paterculus and Pliny. 
                Give me authors who portray characters as if by showing them before the eyes. And in this lively category of description Livy excels also, as 
                a nearly unique craftsman of ‘imaging’ [i.e. the representation of the characteristics a person].
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
